# LESSON 2 requests.  Server: npm run server  (from lesson/)
# In VS Code with the REST Client extension, a Send Request link appears above
# each one. Postman works just as well.
#
# The server runs on 3001, the same port the class project uses. There is no
# /api here: that prefix belongs to the client, and Vite strips it before the
# request arrives. See client/vite.config.js.

@host = http://localhost:3001


### 1. POST a new animal
# The endpoint this lesson builds. Before step 3 is written this returns 404,
# which is a useful thing to show first.

POST {{host}}/add-one-animal
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "name": "Falcon",
    "category": "Bird",
    "can_fly": true,
    "lives_in": "Cliffs"
}


### 2. POST another, to show the id counting up
# The id is never sent. The database generates it, which is what SERIAL means.

POST {{host}}/add-one-animal
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "name": "Otter",
    "category": "Mammal",
    "can_fly": false,
    "lives_in": "Rivers"
}


### 3. POST with no name
# name is NOT NULL in the table, so the database refuses this row.
#
# Express 5 catches the failure and answers 500 on its own, which is worth
# seeing: the server stays up, and the reply tells you what the database said.
# Checking for a missing name before the query, and answering 400 instead, is
# what you would add next.

POST {{host}}/add-one-animal
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "category": "Bird",
    "can_fly": true,
    "lives_in": "Nowhere"
}


### 4. POST with no Content-Type header
# Worth showing on purpose. Nothing parses the body, so req.body is empty and
# every value is undefined. The database refuses it for the same reason as
# above, but the cause is entirely different, and that is the lesson.

POST {{host}}/add-one-animal

{
    "name": "Sparrow",
    "category": "Bird",
    "can_fly": true,
    "lives_in": "Hedges"
}
